Goals

In mass cytometry, a small level of crosstalk between channels can occur. Mainly in the channels: - +1/-1, - And isotope impurities e.g. Sm152 with other Sm isotopes. - +16 due to oxidation products.

During data acquisition, this spillover is measured using a spillover compensation slide where each spot contains a single metal isotope. Here, this spillover measured and correction is applied to the measured cell counts, as described in the original publication.

This script is based on the IMC data analysis workflow.

Read in the spillover compensation slide

Since, the Hyperion-XTi, IMC data is only outputted as .mcd, not .txt anymore, breaking standard pipelines. Therefore, we have converted the .mcds files to .tiffs files (without HPF) using the steinbock package. Now, we continue with the .tiffs.

Always identify for a given spot, the column with the highest value and assign it to the corresponding metal.

## Identifying strongest metal.
results <- total |> 
  group_by(spot_id) |>
  summarise(across(1:(nrow(panel)-1), \(.x) mean(.x, na.rm = TRUE))) |> 
  tidyr::pivot_longer(cols = 2:(nrow(panel)), names_to = "metal", values_to = "intensity") |> 
  group_by(spot_id) |>
  summarise(metal = metal[which.max(intensity)])

Spillover heatmaps

Next, the median pixel intensities per spot are plotted and thresholded on medians higher than 200 counts. Low median intensities (< 200 counts) can hinder robust spillover estimation, in which case consecutive pixels can be binned.

The median pixel intensity per channel should be highest for the corresponding metal. If this is not the case, either the .TXT file name is incorrect or the wrong metal isotope was spotted on the spillover compensation slide.

imcRtools::plotSpotHeatmap(sce, spot_id = "metal", statistic = "mean", cluster_rows = FALSE, cluster_cols= FALSE, 
  order_metals = TRUE)

plotSpotHeatmap(sce, spot_id = "metal", log = FALSE, threshold = 100)

Pixel binning

Consecutive pixels are summed to increase the robustness of the spillover estimation. No signal should be observed off the diagonal on the thresholded heatmap. If that is the case, reduce the bin size.

# Pixel binning
bin_size <- 20

sce <- binAcrossPixels(sce, spot_id = "metal", bin_size = bin_size)
assay(sce, "exprs") <- asinh(counts(sce)/5)

## Plot binned heatmaps.
plotSpotHeatmap(sce, spot_id = "metal", statistic = "mean", cluster_rows = FALSE, cluster_cols= FALSE, 
  order_metals = TRUE, assay_type = "counts")

## Binned + Thresholded heatmaps:
plotSpotHeatmap(sce, spot_id = "metal", log = FALSE, threshold = 200, 
  cluster_rows = FALSE, cluster_cols= FALSE, order_metals = TRUE, assay_type = "counts")

Filter pixels

Debarcoding and pixel assignment

Pixels are assigned to their corresponding “barcode” (in this case the already known metal isotope spot). This allows to identify pixels that cannot be robustly assigned to the spotted metal. These background pixels are removed prior to spillover estimation:
1. Assign a preliminary metal mass to each pixel.
2. For each pixel, estimate a cutoff parameter for the distance between positive and negative pixel sets.
3. Apply the estimated cutoffs to identify truly positive pixels.

# Get correct key.
bc_key <- as.numeric(unique(sce$sample_mass))
bc_key <- bc_key[order(bc_key)]

sce <- assignPrelim(sce, bc_key = bc_key)

Compute spillover matrix

Compute and plot spillover matrix

Functions from the CATALYST package are used to compute the spillover matrix and visualize it.

sce <- computeSpillmat(sce)

isotope_list <- CATALYST::isotope_list
isotope_list$Ar <- 80

plotSpillmat(sce, isotope_list = isotope_list)

Save Spillover matrix in the metadata of the SCE object + as external csv.

# Save spillover matrix in variable
sm <- metadata(sce)$spillover_matrix

write.csv(sm, "sm.csv")

Compute spillover matrix

Compute and plot spillover matrix

Functions from the CATALYST package are used to compute the spillover matrix and visualize it.

# Apply spillover compensation per batch. This takes considerable time.
rowData(spe)$channel_name <- paste0(rowData(spe)$metal, "Di")
spillmat <- metadata(sce)$spillover_matrix
metadata(spe)$spillover_matrix <- spillmat

spe <- CATALYST::compCytof(spe, spillmat, transform = FALSE, cofactor = 1,
                            isotope_list = isotope_list, overwrite = FALSE)

# Extract compensated counts
comp_counts <- assay(spe, "compcounts")

# Overwrite the compensated counts
assay(spe, "raw") <- assay(spe, "counts")
assay(spe, "counts") <- comp_counts

# Write to exprs:
assay(spe, "exprs_pre") <- asinh(assay(spe, "raw")/5)
assay(spe, "exprs") <- asinh(assay(spe, "counts")/5)
library(dittoSeq)
library(patchwork)
before <- dittoScatterPlot(spe, x.var = "CD4", y.var = "CD31",
                           assay.x = "exprs_pre", assay.y = "exprs") +
    ggtitle("Before compensation")

after <- dittoScatterPlot(spe, x.var = "CD4", y.var = "CD31",
                          assay.x = "exprs", assay.y = "exprs") +
    ggtitle("After compensation")
before + after
